The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Thursday, August 26, 2004 				 HCL Info net surges 89%
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, Aug. 25: HCL Infosystems registered an 89 per cent jump in net profit at Rs 175.1 crore for the financial year ended June 30, 2004. Last year, it had posted a net profit of Rs 92.7 crore.																								The consolidated revenue of the company rose 63 per cent to Rs 4,413 crore from Rs 2,705.1 crore in the year-ago period.																								Announcing the results, Ajai Chowdhry, chairman and CEO, HCL Infosystems, said, A lot of people have been obsessed with the export of IT, which has been fantastic for the country, but it is time that we all should pay attention to the domestic market. Last year, we decided to do that, which is reflected in our growth and hence this result.																								Both the industry and the government need to pay attention to create a big Indian IT domestic industry. The potential, opportunity is large and we have just scratched the surface, Chowdhry said.																								In India, there are only 11 personal computers per 1000 people, while in China there are 100 PC per 1000 people and in the US it is 500-600 PC per 1000 people.																								The potential is to hit the Chinese number. Currently, we sell three million PCs each year, while China sells about 14 million PCs, he said. The total installed base of PCs in India is 25 million.																								The revenue from the computer systems business grew by 38 per cent at Rs 1,523.3 crore as against Rs 1,103.7 crore in the previous year.																								HCL Infosystems revenue from office automation and telecommunication segments alone grew by 89 per cent at Rs 2,876.8 crore during 2003-04 against Rs 1,521.6 crore in the previous year.																								While profits grew by 34 per cent at Rs 45.9 crore during the quarter ended June 30 against Rs 34.2 crore in the same period last year. 
